 and ethnographic research approach, reveals dynamic interaction between learners’ agency and contextual conditions underlying the participants’ strategic learning process. Such understanding informs pedagogical efforts to foster individual learners’ capacity for strategic learning and their capacities in opening up and sustaining a social learning space for exercising their strategic learning capacity or utilizing their strategic learning knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish language -- Acquisition -- Methodology. 0aEnglish language -- Study and teaching (Higher) -- China. 0aEnglish language -- Study and teaching (Higher) -- Chinese speakers. 0aEnglish languagexAcquisitionxMethodology. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teaching (Higher)xChinese speakers. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teaching (Higher)zChina. 0aSecond language acquisition -- Methodology. 0aSecond language acquisitionxMethodology. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aL2 strategies.  aSLA.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  aagency.  aforeign language learning.  aindividual differences.  asecond language learning.  astrategic language learning.  astrategy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066313608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060671340uhttps://doi.org/10.21832/978184769245040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847692450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847692450/original  a978-3-11-060671-3  MultiLingual Matters eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066313-6  MultiLingual Matters Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBA